In TypeScript, you can use the `as` operator to assert a type, which tells the type system that you know the value will have a specific type, even though it may have multiple types in theory. For example, if you have a variable that can be either a string or a number, but you know it will only be a string in practice, you can use the `as` operator to assert its type as a string:
```typescript
let value: string | number = 42;
value = "Hello, world!";
console.log(value.length); // This works because TypeScript knows that value is a string now
value = value as string;
console.log(value.length); // This also works because we've asserted that value is a string
```
